text: Honestly, the movie looks like shit, but I don't get all the comments calling this "feminist" or "the black version of..." There was no political message at all in that trailer and if you're calling it "feminist" because it's a woman being a badass with guns, look up female Soviet snipers in WWII. There were Russian female snipers with hundreds of confirmed Nazi kills.   As far as this being a "black version of..." again, there was no racially political commentary at all in the trailer. If you think an action movie with black actors is somehow a black version of something else, then you're an idiot. The trailer looked as generic as fuck. Some badass, well-armed assassin/warrior kicks ass against a bunch of bad guys. How many times has that formula been used in movies, TV shows, books and video games? Countless times. Not to mention that the 70s were full of movies like this...with mostly black casts. Check out Pam Grier's IMDB filmography and you'll see.   So yeah, the trailer itself looked like mediocre, B-movie schlock, but so do trailers for most movies that come out.

text: I'm Black. So proud of it. I always support black film (Go check out Sleight if you haven't already) I love seeing my people on the up and up. But sadly, we live in a capitalist society. Atomic blonde is doing well. I'm definitely going to go see it. So, instead of doing something different, like playing with the aesthetic of the film, which would've been smart (setting it in the 80's or 70's or even the 50's) they just retread things to try and be culturally appropriate. Nope. It's not working man...even using the old school 70's inspired font for "Proud Marry" at the end is just wack. Give us a black character that could compete with James Bond, John Wick, or any other movie icon without copying the other films beat for beat even all the way down to the way the trailer is edited. THIS IS NOT BABY DRIVER! BE YOUR OWN FILM! I mean look, it's very early. This is the first trailer and maybe the story could be good, we'll see about that...but I'm kind of over Hollywood's lack of creativity and originality. I want more. I expect more. We need more Jordan Peele's and Ava Duvernay's. Visionaries.

author: John Cunningham

text: Okay I can't speak for everyone else, but this is my problem with the movie (yes I know it hasn't even come out yet): My problem isn't that the lead is a woman or that she's black (cuz I'm not a jackass). It's that this movie looks generic as hell. We've gotten so many of these movies about these one-man (or woman) badass killing machines (Taken, Salt, The Transporter, Non-Stop, John Wick, Atomic Blonde just to name a few) recently. And the creators probably think they'll get away with this one and maybe even be praised for making it just because they went "Hey lets do that, but make the lead an African American female." We don't need another one of these movies, we want originality. We want something we've never seen before. One could argue "Well you've probably never seen this before" and to that I say no I have. Just when I saw it before the lead was a guy and white.   And I am all for gender equality in movies and everywhere else, but if you want an empowering female lead:  1. Do something original  2. Stop praising yourself for doing it so much.  - Seriously about this one (The "P    M____ Proud Mary" thing was a bit over the top. Again, totally for gender equality, but stop patting yourself on the back so much. If the movie is good it will speak for itself. You don't need to shove it down our throats with your gimmicks and shit. Neither Wonder Woman nor the Hunger Games did this. And they were both great (at least until Mockingly part 1 and 2). They didn't need to go *"HEY HEY LOOK AT US WE'RE MAKING A FILM WITH A STRONG FEMALE LEAD THAT"S KICKIN ASS ALL THE TIME GIVE US YOUR PRAISE FOR BEING REVOLUTIONARY."* They were just good movies that people went to see because they were good. They just happened to have a lead that was a female that kicked all the ass.   Also it doesn't help that this movie looks cheesy and cheap as hell.

text: I think, because John Wick set such a high and satisfactory standard it's hard for us to see these actors we know well to act the same. See, James Bond set the standard or a serious badass womanizing spy. Kingsman set a fun ass action flick full of new standards. John Wick... John Wick obliterated stand alone badass competition. I'm sure these films aren't bad, (atomic blonde, Mary) It just feels they're trying to ride the camelhump of its success and kick start their own series. Salt was good as hell and that was a woman. I feel these movies could have been done a bit differently. She's a great actress, but had they brought a fresh face nobody knows, then it would've have helped but not change the fact. But action after action after action, John Wick beat it and it's hard to not see it as anything but dick riding the hype. Let me know if I'm wrong, I stand by my two cents.

text: Snowflake chumps in comment sections defending obvious John Wick coat tail riding by trying to make it seem like blaxploitation films were good things. The era was about exploiting the "black rage" against white society in order to FILL THEATER SEATS. They sold out their own kind and abused a vulnerable national wound TO MAKE A PROFIT. The producers of this film will no doubt mention those films when promoting this and every single rich white interviewer will nod and go "wow yeah so cool". You all need a perspective realignment. This is a film, a corporate product that must have a return on investment. If you think this movie or ANY movie is a mantra of empowerment you are exactly the type of delusional popcorn muncher they want to pay for their movie. Blaxploitation is racism, and this is an attempt to cash in on the hot new stylish action hero phase. Fast editing and "gearing up" montages. Typography and logo design is usually one of the last things done with a film and here it's the only thing tying it to that era you are all trying to defend.
